{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12324"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12324"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.41,0.39,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33148"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man is brought into the emergency department after falling off his motorbike and injuring his back. He is fully conscious, alert and oriented. His blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse 120/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The only abnormality on examination is tenderness in his right flank and microscopic haematuria. An urgent CT scan is ordered (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the grade of renal trauma in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Grade 1","Grade 2","Grade 3","Grade 4","Grade 5"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a long laceration (\u0026gt;4cm) with haematoma extending into the inferior aspect of the renal pelvis. The most common classification followed for renal trauma is the AAST classification which divides renal trauma into five stages. This patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Egrade 3 renal trauma\u003C/strong\u003E which is characterised by the presence of a laceration of more than 1 cm without extension into the renal pelvis or collecting system with no evidence of urine extravasation. This CT shows a laceration to the inferior pole of the right kidney, with a contained peri-renal haematoma. Provided there are no other intra-abdominal injuries, these patients should be managed conservatively under close observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe grading of renal trauma facilitates the management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 1 renal trauma \u003C/strong\u003Eis characterised by contusion or non-enlarging subcapsular perirenal haematoma and no laceration. Such patients should be managed conservatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 2 \u003C/strong\u003Econsists of a superficial laceration of less than 1 cm depth that does not involve the collecting system, with no evidence of urine extravasation, non-expanding peri-renal haematoma confined to retroperitoneum. These patients should be managed conservatively with close observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 4\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by lacerations that extend to the renal pelvis or urinary extravasation, injury to the main renal artery or vein with contained haemorrhage, segmental infarctions without associated lacerations and expanding subcapsular haematomas compressing the kidney. These patients are at increased risk of developing hypertension due to a decrease in renal blood flow or compression of renal blood vessels. Some form of surgical intervention is likely to be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrade 5\u003C/strong\u003E is the most serious type of injury and is characterised by a shattered kidney, avulsion of the renal hilum (devascularisation of a kidney due to hilar injury), ureteropelvic avulsions and complete laceration or thrombus of the main renal artery or vein. These patients will require urgent surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Grade 3 renal trauma is characterised by the presence of a laceration of more than 1cm without extension into the renal pelvis or collecting system with no evidence of urine extravasation."],"references":["Gaillard F, Niknejad M, Saber M, et al. AAST kidney injury scale. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 14 Dec 2022) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1972"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12324"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18681"},{"type":"media","id":"18682"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18681"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8524125-350f-421b-b3b2-80eb7abeb9b8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8524125-350f-421b-b3b2-80eb7abeb9b8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18682"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1c07160d-083a-46b7-adc6-dcd0dd800168.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1c07160d-083a-46b7-adc6-dcd0dd800168.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":736,"height":899}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com